messages.content: Tell me about this dandiset. *

This Dandiset, titled **"Allen Institute Openscope - Vision2Hippocampus project"** (DANDI:000690, version 0.250326.0015), investigates how visual information is processed from early sensory regions (like the thalamus and primary visual cortex) through higher visual and hippocampal areas in the mouse brain. The dataset focuses on examining the evolution from simple stimulus representation to more abstract concepts, such as space and events, utilizing a range of visual stimuli—including bars of light and naturalistic movies.

**Key Details:**

- **Species:** Mus musculus (house mouse)
- **Techniques:** Multi-electrode extracellular electrophysiology, large-scale Neuropixels recordings
- **Main Data:** Raw and processed neural signals (ElectricalSeries, LFP, Units, ProcessingModule)
- **Number of files:** 156 NWB files (~600 GB total)
- **Subjects:** 25 mice
- **Stimuli:** Includes both simple (moving bars of different widths/speeds/contrasts, “disco” bars) and complex (movies of eagles and squirrels) visual stimuli.
- **Goal:** To understand how simple and complex visual information is sequentially transformed and represented across the visual pathway, ultimately reaching the hippocampus and related regions.
- **Collaborators:** Allen Institute & Mehta Lab (UCLA), OpenScope collaboration

You can explore individual NWB files from this dataset, view neural data, and learn more about visual processing in mice using resources like [Neurosift](https://neurosift.app/), which allows you to interactively browse the contents of these files.

- [Dandiset on DANDI Archive](https://dandiarchive.org/dandiset/000690/0.250326.0015)

- Citation: Mehta, Mayank R et al. (2025) Allen Institute Openscope - Vision2Hippocampus project, DANDI Archive, 10.48324/dandi.000690/0.250326.0015
